Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Put the @butternut squash{1%unit}(diced) on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle over a little @oil{to taste}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Pop on the top shelf of your #oven{} and roast until golden and tender, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1%unit}(halved, peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Roughly chop the @parsley{10%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Halve the @chilli{1/2%unit}(halved lengthways, deseeded and finely chopped). Deseed and finely chop half (double for 4p).

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Boil 1L @water{to taste} (double for 4p) in a medium #pot{} on high heat.

When boiling add the @vegetable stock{2%sachets}, stir to dissolve and reduce the heat to the lowest setting.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{to taste} in a (separate) large pot on medium heat. Add the onion. Stir and cook until the onion is soft, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Add the chopped chilli (use less if you don't like spice) and garlic, cook for ~{1%minute} more, then stir in the @risotto rice{225%g}.

Cook for ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in a ladle of your stock. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle.

Keep the pot on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time.

The cooking time should take ~{25-30%minutes} and your risotto is done when the rice is al dente—cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

Add additional water if the risotto becomes too dry.

Add the cooked butternut squash, the @grated Italian style hard cheese{50%g}, half the parsley and a knob of @butter{to taste}.

Halve the @lemon{1/2%unit}, add a squeeze of lemon juice, taste and season with salt and pepper.

Serve the butternut squash risotto in #bowls{} with the remaining parsley sprinkled over the top.